n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |William Carr\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} | Independent\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |39,412\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} align=\"right\" |24.21%\n|-\n|2016\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |{{nowrap|'''Morgan Griffith'''}}\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |212,838\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |68.6%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |Derek Kitts\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |87,877\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |28.3%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Janice Allen Boyd\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |Independent\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |9,050\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |2.9%\n|}\n\n==Political positions==\n\n===Immigration===\nGriffith has voted to allow the Commonwealth of Virginia to enforce federal immigration laws to criminalize knowingly employing [[illegal immigrants]] or undocumented workers,<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=3512&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref> and also voted to criminalize possession of firearms by illegal aliens.<ref>[http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp504.exe?041+sum+HB79 Virginia State Legislature archives]</ref>\n\n===Gay rights===\nWhile serving in the Virginia House of Delegates, Griffith supported a constitutional amendment to prohibit same-sex marriage by defining marriage as between one man and one woman.<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=3974&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart website]</ref> He voted in favor of a motion to effectively kill a bill to prohibit discrimination on the basis of [[sexual orientation]] for government employees in Virginia.<ref>[https://votesmart.org/bill/votes/32052#.U0zmiFfiFFY SB 66 \u2013 Prohibiting Sexual Orientation Discrimination in State Government Employment \u2013 Voting Record]</ref>\n\n=== Environment ===\nIn 2017, Griffith voted to nullify the [[Stream Protection Rule]], which included improvements in the protection of water supplies, water quality, streams, fish and other wildlife that have the potential to be negatively affected by surface coal mining.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/115th-congress/house-joint-resolution/38|title=H.J.Res.38 - 115th Congress (2017-2018): Disapproving the rule submitted by the Department of the Interior known as the Stream Protection Rule.|last=Bill|first=Johnson,|date=2017-02-16|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref> That same year, Griffith joined other members of the House of Representatives in passing an amendment to H.R. 3354, which undermined the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]]\u2019s (EPA) ability to enforce environmental standards in the Chesapeake Bay watershed, which covers six states and the District of Columbia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.congress.gov/amendment/115th-congress/house-amendment/354|title=H.Amdt.354 to H.R.3354 - 115th Congress (2017-2018)|last=Bob|first=Goodlatte,|date=2017-09-07|website=www.congress.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.politico.com/newsletters/morning-energy/2018/07/17/spotlight-on-ferc-280874|title=Spotlight on FERC|website=POLITICO|language=en|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n\nGriffith is a proponent of \"an 'all of the above' energy strategy\" that utilizes both fossil fuel and renewable energy sources.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://morgangriffith.house.gov/issues/issue/?IssueID=44643|title=Energy and Environment {{!}} Congressman Morgan Griffith|website=morgangriffith.house.gov|language=en|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref> In 2011, Griffith joined other GOP members in urging Interior Secretary [[Ken Salazar]] to reconsider the ban on offshore drilling off Virginia's coast.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://morgangriffith.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=269371|title=Interior secretary urged to reconsider offshore drilling ban for Virginia|date=2011-11-17|website=U.S. House of Representatives|language=en|access-date=2018-10-12}}</ref>\n\n===Gun rights===\nGriffith voted in favor of several bills to reduce restrictions on gun ownership, including a bill to allow [[concealed weapons]] in vehicles without a permit<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=17236&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref> and to allow concealed weapons permit holders to carry their firearms in restaurants and bars.<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=24056&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref> Griffith also voted to prohibit consumption of alcohol while in possession of a concealed weapon.<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=17240&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref> In 2004 Griffith voted to prohibit carrying firearms or ammunition in the non-secure areas of airport terminals, including baggage claim areas.<ref>[http://www.roanoke.com/roatimes/news/story164105.html www.roanoke.com] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120913190641/http://www.roanoke.com/roatimes/news/story164105.html |date=2012-09-13 }}</ref><ref>[http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp504.exe?041+vot+HV1674+SB0660 Virginia State Legislature archives]</ref>\n\n===Health care===\nEarly in 2010, Griffith voted in favor of a bill to prohibit any [[individual mandate]] to purchase [[health insurance]].<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=28657&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref> This law passed Virginia's legislature before the federal [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] was enacted, which Virginia has used to challenge the individual mandate in federal court.<ref>[http://www.healthleadersmedia.com/content_redirect.cfm?content_id=252184 www.healthleadersmedia.com]</ref> However, on July 17, 2013 Griffith was the lone GOP member of the House to vote against delaying the implementation of the individual mandate.<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2013/07/17/house-votes-to-postpone-individual-mandate-2 U.S. News & World Report: \"House votes to postpone individual mandate\"]</ref>\n\nJust prior to the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013]], Griffith issued press release in which he endorsed the final House version of [[Continuing Appropriations Resolution, 2014]], which would have continued funding for  federal government operations while delaying implementation of the Affordable Care Act.<ref>[http://morgangriffith.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=351857 \"Griffith Statement on Latest House Efforts to Keep the Government Open\"]</ref> Griffith voted against the [[Continuing Appropriations Act, 2014]], the Senate-proposed compromise that ended the shutdown without defunding the Affordable Care Act.<ref>[http://clerk.house.gov/evs/2013/roll550.xml Office of the Clerk of the U.S. House of Representatives: Final Vote Results for Roll Call 550]</ref>\n\n===Death penalty===\nGriffith has voted consistently for expansions of the [[death penalty]] to include eligibility for accomplices to a murder, as well as for those who murder a judge or a witness.<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=12385&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref><ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=12387&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref><ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=24101&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref>\n\n===Abortion===\nWhen surveyed in 1999 on his political positions by [[Project Vote Smart]], Griffith indicated that he supports legalized [[abortion]] in the [[first trimester]] and to save the life of the mother,<ref name=\"vs5148\">[http://www.votesmart.org/npat.php?can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref> while favoring the restriction of abortion through [[Parental notification|parental notification laws]] and prohibition of [[partial-birth abortion]]. Griffith's voting record has generally been consistent with his 1999 survey, voting in favor of restrictions on late term abortions such as parental-notification and parental-consent, while voting against bills that would restrict first-term abortions. In 2010 Griffith voted to restrict state funding of abortions,<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=30562&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref> and to require [[abortion clinic]]s to meet the same licensing requirements as surgical centers. In 2006 Griffith voted to restrict state funding for [[Embryonic stem cell|fetal stem cell research]].<ref>[http://www.votesmart.org/issue_keyvote_detail.php?cs_id=5237&can_id=5148 Project Vote Smart]</ref>\n\nIn 2007 Griffith voted against <ref>[http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp504.exe?071+vot+HV0657+HB2797 Virginia State Legislature archives]</ref> a bill in the [[Virginia General Assembly]], HB 2797, which stated: ''\"That life begins at the moment of fertilization and the right to enjoyment of life guaranteed by Article 1, \u00a7 1 of the Constitution of Virginia is vested in each born and preborn human being from the moment of fertilization\"''<ref>[http://leg1.state.va.us/cgi-bin/legp504.exe?071+ful+HB2797 Virginia State Legislature archives]</ref>\n\nGriffith's 2010 campaign website reported that Griffith has a \"100% pro-life\" voting record and an \"A\" rating from the [[Virginia Society for Human Life]] (VSHL). However, VSHL's report on 2007 legislation in Virginia omits reference to HB 2797<ref>[http://www.12cups.org/vshlpac/vshl.org/elections/2007/2007_Va_House_of_Delegates_Vote_Key.shtml www.12cups.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724202816/http://www.12cups.org/vshlpac/vshl.org/elections/2007/2007_Va_House_of_Delegates_Vote_Key.shtml |date=2011-07-24 }}</ref> Project Vote Smart indicated that Griffith declined to take their survey again in 2010.<ref name=\"vs5148\" />\n\n===Taxes and spending===\nGriffith supports raising the retirement age and reducing the number of American troops serving overseas as means of reducing the federal budget deficit.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.tricities.com/news/2011/jul/14/local-congressmen-react-debt-talks-ar-1172832/ |title=Local congressmen react to debt talks |author=Melissa Hipolit|date= 14 July 2011|work= TriCities.com|publisher= |accessdate=18 July 2011}}</ref>  Most recently, Griffith voted in favor of the November 2017 tax plan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/11/16/us/politics/house-vote-republican-tax-bill.html/ |title=How Every Member Voted on the House Tax Bill|author=K.K. REBECCA LAI|date= 16 November 2017|work= New York Times|publisher= |accessdate=2 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Medical marijuana===\nIn 2014, Griffith introduced legislation to move marijuana from a Schedule I to a Schedule II narcotic, which would effectively make the drug legal for medical purposes under federal law.<ref>{{cite news|last=Jackman|first=Tom|title=Va. Rep. Griffith introduces federal \u2018Legitimate Use of Medicinal Marijuana Act\u2019|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/local/wp/2014/04/30/va-rep-griffith-introduces-federal-legitimate-use-of-medicinal-marijuana-act/|accessdate=2 May 2014|newspaper=Washington Post|date=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGriffith is married to the former Hilary Davis. The couple has three children. He is [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]].<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/5148/morgan-griffith#.UgIobNI3tMc]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://morgangriffith.house.gov/ Congressman Morgan Griffith] official U.S. House site\n* [http://morgangriffithforcongress.com/ Morgan Griffith for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Virginia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Morgan_Griffith_%5BR-9%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=G000568 | votesmart=5148 | fec=H0VA09055 | congress=h-griffith/2070 }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://ballotpedia.org/Morgan_Griffith Biography] at [[Ballotpedia]]\n* [http://www.nndb.